    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{x^{3}+64}{x^{2}-16}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{x^{2}-4x+16}{x-4}, x\ne -4</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors.</p>
<p>It<rsq/>s good to know the sum and difference of cubes formulas:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ x^{3}+y^{3} = (x+y)(x^2-xy+y^2) }</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ x^{3}-y^{3} = (x-y)(x^2+xy+y^2) }</m></p>
<p>When you see <lq/>cube<rq/> and perfect cube numbers, like <m>1, 8, 27, 64, 125, ...</m>, you should know the above two formulas could help you.</p>
<p>Here is the solution for this problem:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{x^{3}+64}{x^{2}-16}} \amp = \frac{{\left(x+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}-4x+16\right)}}{{\left(x+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}} \\
                     \amp = {\frac{x^{2}-4x+16}{x-4}, x\ne -4}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>x+4</m> was crossed out, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>x \ne -4</m>.</p>
</solution>
